What is a spinlock?

A spinlock allows only one thread or CPU core at a time to enter a critical section. If another thread tries to acquire the lock while it's already held, it repeatedly checks ("spins") until the lock becomes available.

//code snippet
spin_lock(&my_lock);

    /* Critical section */
    shared_variable++;

    spin_unlock(&my_lock);
    
    
    Why "spin"?

Unlike a mutex, a thread waiting on a spinlock does not sleep. Instead, it continuously loops:
This avoids the overhead of putting a thread to sleep and waking it up, making spinlocks useful when:

The lock is expected to be held for a very short time.
Sleeping is not allowed (e.g., interrupt context in the kernel).
Multiple CPU cores may access the same data

spinlock_t is an opaque type; kernel code normally manipulates it through APIs such as:

spin_lock()
spin_unlock()
spin_trylock()
spin_lock_irqsave()
spin_unlock_irqrestore()

spinlock vs mutex

| Feature                              | Spinlock           | Mutex                      |
| ------------------------------------ | ------------------ | -------------------------- |
| Wait behavior                        | Busy-waits (spins) | Sleeps                     |
| Suitable for short critical sections | Yes                | Usually                    |
| Can be used in interrupt context     | Yes                | No                         |
| CPU usage while waiting              | High               | Low                        |
| Kernel-only primitive                | Commonly           | Both kernel and user space |


Holding a spinlock for too long is harmful because waiting CPUs consume processor time while spinning. Therefore critical sections protected by spinlock_t should be kept extremely short.

| Function                   | Purpose                                |
| -------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| `spin_lock(&lock)`         | Acquire the lock; spin until available |
| `spin_unlock(&lock)`       | Release the lock                       |
| `spin_trylock(&lock)`      | Try to acquire without waiting         |
| `spin_lock_irqsave()`      | Acquire lock and disable interrupts    |
| `spin_unlock_irqrestore()` | Release lock and restore interrupts    |


When someone says spinlock_t is an opaque type, they mean that code using spinlock_t is not supposed to depend on its internal structure or representation.

For example, in many operating systems or libraries you might see:

spinlock_t lock;
spin_lock(&lock);
...
spin_unlock(&lock);

but you are not expected to access fields inside lock directly, such as:

lock.some_internal_field = 1; 

What is an opaque type?

An opaque type hides its implementation details from users of the API. Users can:

Declare variables of the type.
Pass them to functions.
Store pointers to them.

But they should not rely on the internal layout.

Benefits include:

Encapsulation: implementation details stay private.
Portability: internals can change without breaking user code.
Safety: prevents incorrect manipulation of internal state

In the context of spinlock_t

A spinlock is a synchronization primitive used to protect shared data. The exact implementation of spinlock_t may differ depending on:

CPU architecture
Kernel version
Debug configuration
Operating system

In some systems (such as certain kernel headers), the full definition may technically be visible, but it is still treated as logically opaque: you should use the API and not touch its internals directly.

Example of a truly opaque type

A common pattern is:

/* header.h */
typedef struct spinlock spinlock_t;

The structure definition is hidden in a source file:

/* source.c */
struct spinlock {
    int state;
};
